<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="nomenclatural notes">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Nomenclatural notes.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
The taxonomic circumscription of 
<taxonomicName genus="X." lsidName="X. caeruleum" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="species" species="caeruleum">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">X. caeruleum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is greatly impaired by the lack of knowledge of the current whereabouts of the type material of several of its associated synonyms. Types for the names 
<taxonomicName genus="X." lsidName="X. caeruleum" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="species" species="caeruleum">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">X. caeruleum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName genus="X." lsidName="X. fockeanum" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="species" species="fockeanum">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">X. fockeanum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
were successfully located and designated by 
<bibRefCitation author="Maas, PJM" journalOrPublisher="Neotropica" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" pagination="1 - 44" refId="B27" refString="Maas, PJM, Maas-van de Kamer, H, 1993. Haemodoraceae. Fl. Neotropica 61: 1 - 44" title="Haemodoraceae. Fl." volume="61" year="1993">Maas and Maas-van de Kamer (1993)</bibRefCitation>
, while types for the names 
<taxonomicName genus="X." lsidName="X. rubrum" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="species" species="rubrum">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">X. rubrum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName authority="Willd. ex Baker, 1876" authorityName="Kuntze" authorityYear="1898" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Asphodelaceae" genus="Eccremis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Viridiplantae" lsidName="Eccremis scabra" order="Asparagales" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Streptophyta" rank="species" species="scabra">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Eccremis scabra</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Boeckeler" authorityYear="1896" baseAuthorityName="Boeckeler" class="Leotiomycetes" family="Tympanidaceae" genus="Durandia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Fungi" lsidName="Durandia macrophylla" order="Helotiales" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Ascomycota" rank="species" species="macrophylla">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Durandia macrophylla</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
were located by us and had lectotypes designated when necessary. Nonetheless, we have been unable to locate a type specimen, or illustration for 
<taxonomicName genus="X." lsidName="X. giganteum" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="species" species="giganteum">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">X. giganteum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, which prevents us from knowing if this name matches any of the 
<taxonomicName genus="X." lsidName="X. caeruleum" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="species" species="caeruleum">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">X. caeruleum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
morphs recognised by us.
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
<bibRefCitation author="Maas, PJM" journalOrPublisher="Neotropica" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" pagination="1 - 44" refId="B27" refString="Maas, PJM, Maas-van de Kamer, H, 1993. Haemodoraceae. Fl. Neotropica 61: 1 - 44" title="Haemodoraceae. Fl." volume="61" year="1993">Maas and Maas-van de Kamer (1993)</bibRefCitation>
erroneously designated plate 66 from 
<bibRefCitation author="Lindley, J" journalOrPublisher=", Leipzig, London, Milano &amp; New York" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" refId="B25" refString="Lindley, J, 1846. New Garden Plant. Edwards's Botanical Register 32: page prior to t. 67." title="New Garden Plant. Edwards's Botanical Register 32: page prior to t. 67." year="1846">Lindley (1846)</bibRefCitation>
as the lectotype of 
<taxonomicName genus="X." lsidName="X. giganteum" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="species" species="giganteum">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">X. giganteum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. The indicated plate actually depicts 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Fabaceae" genus="Swainsona" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Swainsona greyana" order="Fabales" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="greyana">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Swainsona greyana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Lindl. (
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Fabaceae" genus="Swainsona" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="" order="Fabales" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="family">Fabaceae</taxonomicName>
) and obviously cannot be the type for 
<taxonomicName genus="X." lsidName="X. giganteum" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="species" species="giganteum">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">X. giganteum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. In fact, the original publication (
<bibRefCitation author="Lindley, J" journalOrPublisher=", Leipzig, London, Milano &amp; New York" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" refId="B25" refString="Lindley, J, 1846. New Garden Plant. Edwards's Botanical Register 32: page prior to t. 67." title="New Garden Plant. Edwards's Botanical Register 32: page prior to t. 67." year="1846">Lindley 1846</bibRefCitation>
) provides no illustration for 
<taxonomicName genus="X." lsidName="X. giganteum" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="species" species="giganteum">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">X. giganteum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. 
<bibRefCitation author="Lindley, J" journalOrPublisher=", Leipzig, London, Milano &amp; New York" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" refId="B25" refString="Lindley, J, 1846. New Garden Plant. Edwards's Botanical Register 32: page prior to t. 67." title="New Garden Plant. Edwards's Botanical Register 32: page prior to t. 67." year="1846">Lindley (1846)</bibRefCitation>
mentions that a live specimen was brought from Caraccas and flowered in Syon [Park], London, UK. After searching for specimens that matched these data at K herbarium, we were unable to locate any. We have also searched for a possible unpublished illustration that might serve as the type for 
<taxonomicName genus="X." lsidName="X. giganteum" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="species" species="giganteum">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">X. giganteum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, but were also unsuccessful. Thus, we are currently unable to designate a lectotype for 
<taxonomicName genus="X." lsidName="X. giganteum" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="species" species="giganteum">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">X. giganteum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, since this name completely lacks any original material (Art. 9.4., 
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.12705/Code.2018" author="Turland, NJ" journalOrPublisher="The New York Botanical Garden, New York" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" refId="B63" refString="Turland, NJ, Wiersema, JH, Barrie, FR, Greuter, W, Hawksworth, DL, Herendeen, PS, Knapp, S, Kusber, W-H, Li, D-Z, Marhold, K, May, TW, McNeill, J, Monro, AM, Prado, J, Price, MJ, Smith, GF, 2018. (2018) International Code of Nomenclature for algae, fungi, and plants (Shenzhen Code) adopted by the Nineteenth International Botanical Congress Shenzhen, China, July 2017. Regnum Vegetabile 159. Koeltz Botanical Books, Glashuetten. https://doi.org/10.12705/Code.2018" title="(2018) International Code of Nomenclature for algae, fungi, and plants (Shenzhen Code) adopted by the Nineteenth International Botanical Congress Shenzhen, China, July 2017. Regnum Vegetabile 159. Koeltz Botanical Books, Glashuetten." url="https://doi.org/10.12705/Code.2018" year="2018">Turland et al. 2018</bibRefCitation>
). Since the original description is not enough to undoubtedly apply this name, we also feel it is premature to designate a neotype until natural populations from Caraccas have been studied. Finally, we also choose to tentatively retain it under the synonymy of 
<taxonomicName genus="X." lsidName="X. caeruleum" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="species" species="caeruleum">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">X. caeruleum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
until further information becomes available.
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
As explained by 
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.1002/tax.594022" author="Dorr, LJ" journalOrPublisher="Taxon" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" pagination="1245 - 1262" refId="B10" refString="Dorr, LJ, Wiersema, JH, 2010. Names of American vascular plants published in Loefling's Iter Hispanicum (1758) and its German translation (1766). Taxon 59 (4): 1245 - 1262, DOI: https://doi.org/10.1002/tax.594022" title="Names of American vascular plants published in Loefling's Iter Hispanicum (1758) and its German translation (1766)." url="https://doi.org/10.1002/tax.594022" volume="59" year="2010">Dorr and Wiersema (2010)</bibRefCitation>
, 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Tingidae" genus="Ixia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Ixia xiphidium" order="Hemiptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="xiphidium">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Ixia xiphidium</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Loefl. represents a misinterpretation by 
<bibRefCitation author="Maas, PJM" journalOrPublisher="Neotropica" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" pagination="1 - 44" refId="B27" refString="Maas, PJM, Maas-van de Kamer, H, 1993. Haemodoraceae. Fl. Neotropica 61: 1 - 44" title="Haemodoraceae. Fl." volume="61" year="1993">Maas and Maas-van de Kamer (1993)</bibRefCitation>
of 
<bibRefCitation author="Loefling, P" journalOrPublisher="Ttryckt pa Direct &amp; Lars Salvii Kostnad, Stockholm" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" refId="B26" refString="Loefling, P, 1758. Iter Hispanicum. Ttryckt pa Direct &amp; Lars Salvii Kostnad, Stockholm" title="Iter Hispanicum." year="1758">
<normalizedToken originalValue="Loefling’s">Loefling's</normalizedToken>
(1758)
</bibRefCitation>
publication. The author never intended to publish a new species but published a new genus, rejecting the application of 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Tingidae" genus="Ixia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Ixia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Ixia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
L. for American plants. Thus, 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Tingidae" genus="Ixia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Ixia xiphidium" order="Hemiptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="xiphidium">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Ixia xiphidium</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Loefl. was never published and should not be included in databases.
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
When describing 
<taxonomicName genus="X." lsidName="X. rubrum" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="species" species="rubrum">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">X. rubrum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="Don, D" journalOrPublisher="Edinburgh New Philosophical Journal" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" pagination="233 - 244" refId="B9" refString="Don, D, 1832. On the characters and affinities of certain genera in the Flora Peruviana. Edinburgh New Philosophical Journal 13: 233 - 244" title="On the characters and affinities of certain genera in the Flora Peruviana." volume="13" year="1832">Don (1832)</bibRefCitation>
mentions his new species is based on a Ruiz &amp; 
<normalizedToken originalValue="Pavón">Pavon</normalizedToken>
collection, but without indicating a collection number or herbarium information. We came across a specimen matching the protologue with a label in 
<normalizedToken originalValue="Pavón’s">Pavon's</normalizedToken>
handwriting during a visit to BM, saying, &quot; 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
<taxonomicName class="Liliopsida" family="Asparagaceae" genus="Ornithogalum" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Ornithogalum rubrum" order="Asparagales" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="rubrum">Ornithogalum rubrum</taxonomicName>
sp. n.
</emphasis>
, 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Fl. Per.</emphasis>
&quot;. This specimen is here selected as the lectotype.
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
<bibRefCitation author="Kuntze, CEO" journalOrPublisher=", Leipzig, London, Milano &amp; New York" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" refId="B23" refString="Kuntze, CEO, 1898. Revisio Generum Plantarum, Vol. 3, part 3. Arthur Felix &amp; al., Leipzig, London, Milano &amp; New York" title="Revisio Generum Plantarum, Vol. 3, part 3. Arthur Felix &amp; al." year="1898">Kuntze (1898)</bibRefCitation>
described 
<taxonomicName authority="Willd. ex Baker, 1876" authorityName="Kuntze" authorityYear="1898" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Asphodelaceae" genus="Eccremis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Viridiplantae" lsidName="Eccremis scabra" order="Asparagales" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Streptophyta" rank="species" species="scabra">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Eccremis scabra</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, based on a collection from 
<normalizedToken originalValue="Río">Rio</normalizedToken>
Juntas, Bolivia. The author mentions a specimen at B, but we were unable to locate it, and it might have been lost during WWII. Luckily, we were able to locate a duplicate at NY, which is designated here as the lectotype.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="distribution">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Distribution and habitat.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
<taxonomicName class="Liliopsida" family="Haemodoraceae" genus="Xiphidium" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Xiphidium caeruleum" order="Commelinales" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="caeruleum">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Xiphidium caeruleum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is widely distributed in the Neotropics, ranging from Mexico, reaching the Antilles, to northern South America (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 25" captionStartId="F25" captionText="Figure 25. Distribution of Xiphidium caeruleum Aubl. Beige - Temperate Coniferous Forests and Boreal Forests; Yellow - Temperate Grasslands, Savannahs and Shrublands; Pink - Temperate Broadleaf and Mixed Forests; Light Green - Subtropical Coniferous Forests; Red - Deserts, Xeric Shrublands and Tropical Coniferous Forests; Orange - Tropical / Subtropical Grasslands, Savannahs and Shrublands; Maroon - Dry Broadleaf Forests; Green - Moist Broadleaf Forests; Lilac - Montane Grasslands and Shrublands." figureDoi="10.3897/phytokeys.169.57996.figure25" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/481951" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">25</figureCitation>
). It can be found growing in permanently or seasonally-wet environments, more rarely in dry and rocky environments.
</paragraph>
